Eigenvector centrality¶

  • Find the 5 most central philosophers according to eigenvector centrality. Calculate centrality corresponding to both in- and out-edges. How is eigenvector centrality different from degree centrality? Compare your results for eigenvector centrality to the results for betweenness centrality - does the difference make sense when you read the philosopher's wikipedia pages?

The code below calculates the Eigenvector centrality for both in-edges and out-edges. The top 5 for in-edges are similar to the betweenness centrality calculated above, which makes sense as both can be interpreted as being a "popular" philosopher. The top 5 for the out-edges consists of other names. These are names that link a lot to other philosophers. This means that they will all have a rather long Wikipedia page, as it gives more room for links. This can be confirmed by looking at their pages.

Degree centrality is simply found by looking at the degree of each node. It is this similie to eigenvector centrality. However eigenvector centrality uses the adjacency matrix and looks at the value of the eigenvalue for at given eigenvector. A large eigenvalue means a high eigenvector centrality.

Degree assortativity coefficient¶

  • Is the undirected version of the graph assortative with respect do degree?. Provide an interpretation of your answer!

The degree assortativity coefficient is calculated below.

The coefficient is low which means that philosophers with high degree does not tend to link to other philosophers with high degree and the same for philosophers with low degree.

This is what can be expected as philosophers with low degree ("unpopular" philsophers) would presumably link more to the famous philosophers, which are the one with high degree. There is no reason to assume that philosophers with low degree will link a lot to other philosophers with low degree. Thus the Degree assortativity coefficient will be low and is around -0.1 in this case.

In [5]:

IIb: Betweenness¶

An interesting definition of centrality is betweenness centrality. In a traditional setting, this measure calculates all shortest paths in the network and then each node gets a score according to which fraction of all shortest paths pass through that node.

In this part of the assignment, we create our own version of centrality, based on the source/target pairs in our dataset. Below, we investigate the relationship between navigation centrality and betweenness centrality.

  • First, list the 5 pages with highest navigation centrality.
In [33]:
# Calculating the navigation centrality

# We start by creating a list of lists including all the inner paths
navlist = []
for i in range(len(paths)):
    pathlist=re.split(';', paths[i].split()[3])
    # We ignore human paths that have length shorter than 3
    if len(pathlist)<3:
        continue
    plist = pathlist[1:len(pathlist)-1]
    navlist.append(plist)
# Flatten the list
mergelist = [j for i in navlist for j in i]
# We extract the '<' items included in the list
finalnavlist = [word for word in mergelist if word!='<']

# Count all naviagtion paths that pass through each node to calculate the navigation centrality by definition
counts = Counter(finalnavlist)
most_common_list = counts.most_common()
navcenlist = []
for i in range(len(most_common_list)):
    # Calculate the navigation centrality
    navcenlist.append((most_common_list[i][0],most_common_list[i][1]/len(finalnavlist)))
    # Print out the 5 pages with highest navigation centrality
    if i<5:
        print "%s: %f" %(most_common_list[i][0],most_common_list[i][1]/len(finalnavlist))

United_States: 0.039465
Europe: 0.019316
United_Kingdom: 0.017264
Earth: 0.014102
England: 0.013967

We can see that the two lists are quite alike, with United_States, Europe and United_Kingdom in the first 3 places, and England in the 5th place. The similarity may indicate that to human the importance of these pages are actually true with the reality.

The human didn't realize that France has a quite high betweenness centrality, which is reasonable, because there is lack of reason to put this for most people. Instead the Earth got a high navigation centrality in the 4th place. This is mainly because people from all the countries consider the earth is important as a link to other things.

Also we can see that in the betweenness centrality list, the United_States has a much higher centrality than the second rank, while in the navigation list the centrality doesn't differ so much. This means there are quite much more links linked to United_States than people think.

In [4]:
stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')
list1=[]

# Clean the data files
for i in range(len(data)):
    readfile=data[i]
    # Remove all numbers and punctuations
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(re.sub(r'\W+|\d',' ', readfile))
    # Convert all words to lower case
    tokenslower = [w.lower() for w in tokens]
    # Remove stopwords
    content = [w for w in tokenslower if w not in stopwords]
    list1.append(content)

    tf.append(counter.most_common())
In [25]:
# Multiply tf and idf and get a word,tf-idf list.
tfidf=[] 
for t in range(len(list1)):
    temp=[]
    for i in range(len(tf[t])):
        summ = 0
        # Find the total time that a token appears in the pages
        for p in range(len(wordset)):
            if tf[t][i][0] in wordset[p]:
                summ += 1
        # Calculate the tf-idf value -- tf*idf and append it to the list
        temp.append([tf[t][i][0],tf[t][i][1]/len(list1[t])*math.log(len(list1)/summ)])
    # Now we get this list of lists, with each sublist containning each page's token and tf-idf
    tfidf.append(temp)
In [168]:
# Define the function to calculate cosine similarity
# Here the input is the string of two pages - source and target

def cosine_similarity(source, target):
    # Initialize two vectors to construct the tf-idf vectors
    vector1 = []
    vector2 = []
    # Get the index of the input page name to find its tf-idf
    x = articles.index(source)
    y = articles.index(target)
    tfidf[x] = sorted(tfidf[x])
    tfidf[y] = sorted(tfidf[y])
    for i in range(len(tfidf[x])):
        if tfidf[x][i][0] in wordset[y]:
            vector1.append(tfidf[x][i][1])
    for j in range(len(tfidf[y])):
        if tfidf[y][j][0] in wordset[x]:
            vector2.append(tfidf[y][j][1])
    # Calculate the cosine similarity according to the definition
    dot_product = sum(p*q for p,q in zip(vector1, vector2))
    magnitude = math.sqrt(sum([val**2 for val in vector1])) * math.sqrt(sum([val**2 for val in vector2]))
    if not magnitude:
        return 0
    return dot_product/magnitude

        if pathlist[j] not in articles:

        if pathlist[j+1] not in articles:
            continue
        sim = cosine_similarity(pathlist[j], pathlist[j+1])
        cossim.append(sim)
    allsim.append(np.mean(cossim))

def sentiment(textfile):
    if not isinstance(textfile,list):
        #Load the textfile that should be analyzed
        text1 = io.open(textfile, 'r',encoding='utf-8')
        textlist=text1.read().split()
    else:
        textlist=textfile
    #Remove all numbers.
    nonumbers=re.compile("[^\d]+").findall(' '.join(textlist))
    #Remove everything that is not words and return their lowercase.
    onlywords=re.compile("[\w|']+").findall(' '.join(nonumbers))
    finallist=[w.lower() for w in onlywords]

    #Make a list of all the words in the textfile and their count
    counts = Counter(finallist)
    most_common_list=counts.most_common()

    #Set the score to 0 and the word count to 0.
    score=0
    wordcount=0
    for i in range(len(most_common_list)):
        #Get a word in the textfile that is being scored.
        curword=most_common_list[i]
        #If the list in the text is part of the sentiment wordlist do the following.
        if curword[0] in wordlist:
            #Find the index of the word in the wordlist
            #and then add the score times the number of times the words appear to score
            wordindex=wordlist.index(curword[0])
            #The score is always 2 places further down in the list compared to the word.
            if wordlist[wordindex+2]!='--':
                score+=float(wordlist[wordindex+2])*curword[1]
                wordcount+=curword[1]
    if score==0:
        if not isinstance(textfile,list):
            print "None of the words in %s was in the LabMT wordlist." %textfile
        else:
            print "None of the words in the text file was in the LabMT wordlist."
    else:
        return score/wordcount

The above implementation is tested on Billy Jean. Compared to the video lecture made by Sune these are a bit lower than what he presented. However this is explained by him using a different list with different scores. Billy Jean does however have a higher score than Thriller which was also the case in the video. This suggests that the implementation is working

Sentiment profiles of novels¶

  • Calculate a sentiment profile for the novels in NLPP1e chapter 1. The sentiment profile has sentiment on the y-axis and position in the text on the x-axis. Use a moving average to show how the sentiment changes. Create profiles for sliding windows of length 15 words, 50 words, 100 words, 500 words.
  • Comment on the sentiment profiles. Do they show a similar pattern? What is the effect of changing the size of the sliding window?

The code below is used only on the texts 1,2,3,6 and 9. The other ones we don't consider as novels. For each novel/book the total sentiment is calculated. A plot is then created using 15 words, 50 words, 100 words and 500 words windows as the exercise states.

To do this a function called sentimentprofile is created that divides the text into chunks of the desired size and then calculates the sentiment of each chunk using the sentiment function.

For each of the books 4 plots are created. Below all of these are some comments about the sentiment profiles.

def sentimentprofile(datalist,chunksize):
    #Divide the datalist into chunks
    chunks = [datalist[x:x+chunksize] for x in xrange(0, len(datalist), chunksize)]
    sentimentlist=[]
    #Calculate the sentiment for each chunk.
    for chunk in chunks:
        sentimentlist.append(sentiment(chunk))
    return sentimentlist

Comments about the sentiment profiles

In general by looking at the profiles using only 15 and 50 words windows it is hard to tell anything. They do have a spike sometime, but it seems mostly random. However the 100 and 500 words windows plots has a bit more meaning to them.

For instance by looking at Monty Python and the Holy Grail it seems like the sentiment is increasing a bit over the course of the book.

On the contrary the sentiment in Moby Dick seems to decrease a bit over time.

It is hard to make any sense of the sentiment profile for Sense and Sensibility.

The book of Genesis definetly have a point in the middle of the book where the sentiment is high. This decreases towards the end though.

The Man Who Was Thursday seems to have an often changing sentiment. It starts high, then drops, increases again, falls a bit and then ends with the highest score of the book. This seems like the way you would expect a novel to behave. It is fine in the begining, then some bad things happen during the book and then it ends with a happy ending. This might be completely false as we have not read it. However looking at the sentiment profile it would seem like this is the case.

Looking at the sentiment score for the entire books, they are all around 5.3-5.4. There is therefore very little variation between the total sentiment of the books. This is probably because words like "the, and, an" etc. are dominating. Their score will have a huge influence on the total sentiment score. It is thus a good idea to look at the sentiment profiles instead, as they capture more of the variation between the books.
